```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class BaseConverter {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);

        // Get the number and its base
        System.out.print("Enter the number: ");
        String number = scanner.nextLine();
        System.out.print("Enter the base of the number: ");
        int base = scanner.nextInt();

        // Get the desired base
        System.out.print("Enter the desired base: ");
        int desiredBase = scanner.nextInt();

        // Convert the number to decimal
        int decimal = Integer.parseInt(number, base);

        // Convert the decimal to the desired base
        String convertedNumber = Integer.toString(decimal, desiredBase);

        // Print the converted number
        System.out.println("Converted number: " + convertedNumber);
    }
}
```

In this code, you'll be prompted to enter the number, its base, and the desired base. The code then converts the number from the given base to decimal and further converts it to the desired base using the `Integer.parseInt()` and `Integer.toString()` methods, respectively.

Note: This code assumes that the input number and bases are valid. You may want to add error handling or input validation for a production-ready application.
